How to create and distribute a minimalist CLI tool with Python, Poetry, Click and Pipx

Álvaro Martínez

·

Follow

Published in

clarityai-engineering

·
6 min read
·
Nov 22, 2022

If you’re a software developer who already wrote some basic Python scripts, and you want to bring your automation skills to the next level, this article is for you.

How many times in your day-to-day work as a software developer have you thought: “if I only had a command line tool to execute this!”. On a daily basis, we feel the burden of having to repeat the same steps over and over again. You know that some automation could be implemented, but at the same time, you don’t have enough time or energy to put on a devex hat to create a command line application from scratch.

What if we told you that it doesn’t need to be painful?

The weather CLI application

Imagine this scenario: you live in New York and it’s winter time. Everyday, multiple times a day, you leave your cosy terminal, you open your browser, you enter your favorite weather service, and then you scroll down until you find out whether it’s freezing outside or not. In an ideal world, you’d like to have a command line tool to quickly check the weather without leaving your terminal. However, you’re only willing to invest time to develop it if the entire process would be faster than checking your browser several times a day. Look no further! Today we are building such an app together.

Introducing Poetry and Click

Poetry is a dependency manager for Python that helps you package your application with all required dependencies; if you are coming from a Java background, think of it as some kind of Maven/Gradle for Python.

Click is useful for creating elegant command line executables in Python, using as little code as possible. It’s very powerful and configurable, yet very simple if you only want to construct a basic application.

Together, Poetry and Click are a dream team. We’ll use both tools to create our weather command line app in a matter of minutes.

Installing Python under pyenv

We’ll install Python, not directly but using pyenv, which is a tool that helps you manage several Python versions while encapsulating and isolating them from the system Python installation (deprecated Python 2 is still installed by default on macOS, but we’re sure you don’t want to use it). You can follow these instructions to install the tool and then, to install Python, execute:

$ pyenv install 3.10
$ pyenv global 3.10

To check that you’re using pyenv-managed Python, execute pyenv which Python and check that it prints something like:

/home/your/user/.pyenv/versions/3.10.8/bin/python

Installing Poetry and initializing your project

The best way to install Poetry is to run its official installation script:

$ curl -sSL https://install.python-poetry.org | python3 -

Now you can initialize your shiny new project using:

$ poetry new weather

Take a minute to understand what Poetry just created, especially the pyproject.toml file that describes your app and its dependencies. Again for those with Java background, this is similar in nature to a pom.xml Maven file or a build.gradle file.

Now let’s add a “hello world!” to your project. Create a new cli.py file in the weather directory and add this:

def cli():
  print("Hello world!")
  if __name__ == "__main__":
    cli()

Our first smoke test is to execute this code as a plain Python script:

$ python weather/cli.py

Now let’s do the same, but executing this script via Poetry in a sandboxed environment under an isolated Python-plus-dependencies installation (the so-called virtual environment).

First, to tell Poetry what’s the entry point for your script, add this to pyproject.toml:

[tool.poetry.scripts]
weather = "weather.cli:cli"

Next, create a virtual environment by executing:

$ poetry install

This command creates a new virtual environment with the same Python version as the one used to install Poetry (if you are curious about where the virtual environment has been created, execute poetry env info).

Now we can execute the script via Poetry:

$ poetry run weather

Did it work? Good, let’s move on.

Your first weather app

Let’s add some basic weather functionality to your app. We’ll read New York’s temperature (in Celsius) from the Open-Meteo endpoint and then print it. Easy!

In order to demonstrate how to add an external dependency to our app, we’re going to use the Requests library to call the endpoint instead of the built-in urllib.request. Add this dependency by executing:

$ poetry add requests

And now it’s time to expand our logic, so write this in your weather/cli.py file:

import requests

def cli():
  r = requests.get('https://api.open-meteo.com/v1/forecast?latitude=40.71&longitude=-74.01&current_weather=true')
  if r.status_code == 200:
    print(r.json()["current_weather"]["temperature"])
  else:
    print("Open-Meteo is down!")

Let’s run the app again:

$ poetry run weather

If it worked for you, let’s spice up our script with Click.

Using Click

Now that you have a simple command line app, you want to expand it a little bit more to be able to request any metric provided by Open-Meteo, for any location in the world, following this pattern:

$ weather metric --latitude=XX --longitude=YY

If no location is specified, it will still use New York coordinates — your beloved hometown in this fictional scenario.

Using Click will allow you to add command line arguments to your app in the most efficient way. First of all, start by adding Click to your dependencies:

$ poetry add click

And now extend your logic to include these parameters:

import requests
import click

@click.command()
@click.argument("metric", required=True)
@click.option("--latitude", "-lat", default=40.71, type=float, required=False, help="latitude (in degrees)")
@click.option("--longitude", "-lon", default=-74.01, type=float, required=False, help="longitude (in degrees)")
def cli(metric: str, latitude: float, longitude: float) -> None:
    r = requests.get('https://api.open-meteo.com/v1/forecast?latitude=' + str(latitude) + '&longitude=' + str(longitude) + '&current_weather=true')
    if r.status_code == 200:
        if metric in r.json()["current_weather"]:
            print(r.json()['current_weather'][metric])
        else:
            print("Metric not supported!")
    else:
        print("Open-Meteo is down!")

if __name__ == "__main__":
    cli()

See how easy that was? Command line arguments are available as parameters to the method indicated in your pyproject.toml file. You’re even getting default values and management of required values. Let’s try it:

$ poetry run weather temperature --latitude=52.52 --longitude=13.40

Now you should get a different temperature for Berlin. Did it work? Good! You did it. Notice that you even get documentation out of the box:

$ poetry run weather --help

Using Poetry shell

Executing poetry run weather is cumbersome, what other alternative do we have? We can simply open a subshell with the activated virtual environment by executing poetry shell; and then run our weather application from there:

weather temperature

Testing your new application

To test this in a simple way, we’ll use CliRunner which is a command line runner provided by Click for testing purposes. We’re also going to need pytest, so let’s add it as a development dependency:

$ poetry add pytest --group dev

After that, write a test that will only check if New York’s temperature is between -90º C and +60º C (let’s hope this won’t need to be modified in the future!). Create tests/test_cli.py:

from click.testing import CliRunner
from weather.cli import cli

class TestWeather:
    def test_cli(self):
        runner = CliRunner()
        result = runner.invoke(cli, ["temperature"])
        assert result.exit_code == 0
        assert -90.0 <= float(result.output) <= 60.0

Finally, let’s execute this test:

$ poetry run pytest

Is everything green? Good! But we’re not done yet…

Distributing your application

Now you can easily check the weather, but you feel the need to share this awesome tool with your friends and colleagues. How can you achieve that as easily as you created the app?

pipx will do the trick! Pipx is a tool that takes some Python codebase and encapsulates it in a self-contained virtual environment without external dependencies. First, follow its documentation to install pipx on your local machine; second, upload your weather project to a Git repository. Once you have these two ingredients in place, embrace this magic:

$ pipx install git+https://github.com/clarityai-eng/weather.git

If everything went well, you’ll see this:

These apps are now globally available
— weather
done! ✨ 🌟 ✨

This means that weather is now a proper command line tool that you can use independently of Poetry!

$ weather temperature

In case you ever get tired of knowing so much about the weather, you can also uninstall it:

$ pipx uninstall weather

Recap

  • You learned how to create a Python executable code in a matter of minutes, letting Poetry handle all dependencies for you.
  • You learned how to pass command line parameters to your tool using Click.
  • You learned how to use Pipx to allow anyone to install your app by just providing a Git repository link.
  • You learned GPS coordinates for New York and Berlin 😬

Now you can write all the awesome tools you always dreamed of! To start developing even quicker, you may start from our Git repository containing the source code for the weather app.

Have a nice day!
